tv_ratings_2seasons <- tv_ratings |> 
  group_by(title) |> 
  mutate(maxseason = max(seasonNumber)) |> 
  filter(maxseason >= 2) |> 
  filter(seasonNumber <= 2) |> 
  mutate(season = factor(seasonNumber,
                         levels = c(1, 2),
                         labels = c("First", "Second")))

Different ways of visualizing distributions.

p1 <- ggplot(tv_ratings,
             aes(x = av_rating)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white",
                 binwidth = .5,
                 boundary = 7)

p2 <- ggplot(tv_ratings,
             aes(x = av_rating)) +
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = .5,
                boundary = 7)

p3 <- ggplot(tv_ratings,
             aes(x = av_rating)) +
  geom_density()

p1 / p2 / p3

p1 + p2 + p3

             aes(x = av_rating,

Comparing distributions

c1 <- ggplot(tv_ratings_2seasons,
             aes(x = av_rating,
                 group = season,
                 fill = season)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white",
                 binwidth = .5,
                 boundary = 7)

c2 <- ggplot(tv_ratings_2seasons,
             aes(x = av_rating,
                 group = season,
                 color = season)) +
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = .5,
                boundary = 7)

c3 <- ggplot(tv_ratings_2seasons,
             aes(x = av_rating,
                 group = season,
                 color = season))+
  geom_density()

c1 / c2 / c3

There are alternatives for two-dimensional plots as well.

library(worldfootballR)

epl <- fb_match_results(
  country = "ENG",
  gender = "M",
  season_end_year = 2018:2023 
)  
s1 <- ggplot(epl,
             aes(x = Home_xG,
                 y = Away_xG)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = .2)

s2 <-  ggplot(epl,
              aes(x = Home_xG,
                  y = Away_xG)) +
  geom_bin_2d(binwidth = c(.5, .5))

s1 + s2
